# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: av1-codec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:av1-codec/av1] Like VP9, but unlike H.264 (AVC) and H.265 (HEVC), AV1 has a royalty-free licensing model that does not hinder adoption in open-source projects.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AVIF is an image file format that uses AV1 compression algorithms.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Alliance's motivations for creating AV1 included the high cost and uncertainty involved with the patent licensing of HEVC (also known as H.265), the MPEG-designed codec expected to succeed AVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Additionally, the Alliance's seven founding members – Amazon, Cisco, Google, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Netflix – announced that the initial focus of the video format would be delivery of high-quality web video.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The official announcement of AV1 came with the press release on the formation of the Alliance for Open Media on 1 September 2015.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Only 42 days before, on 21 July 2015, HEVC Advance's initial licensing offer was announced to be an increase over the royalty fees of its predecessor, AVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In addition to the increased cost, the complexity of the licensing process increased with HEVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Unlike previous MPEG standards where the technology in the standard could be licensed from a single entity, MPEG LA, when the HEVC standard was finished, two patent pools had been formed with a third pool on the horizon.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In addition, various patent holders were refusing to license patents via either pool, increasing uncertainty about HEVC's licensing.
[src:av1-codec/av1] According to Microsoft's Ian LeGrow, an open-source, royalty-free technology was seen as the easiest way to eliminate this uncertainty around licensing.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The negative effect of patent licensing on free and open-source software has also been cited as a reason for the creation of AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] For example, building an H.264 implementation into Firefox would prevent it from being distributed free of charge since licensing fees would have to be paid to MPEG-LA.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Free Software Foundation Europe has argued that FRAND patent licensing practices make the free software implementation of standards impossible due to various incompatibilities with free-software licenses.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Many of the components of the AV1 project were sourced from previous research efforts by Alliance members.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Individual contributors had started experimental technology platforms years before: Xiph's/Mozilla's Daala published code in 2010, Google's experimental VP9 evolution project VP10 was announced on 12 September 2014, and Cisco's Thor was published on 11 August 2015.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Building on the code base of VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques, several of which were developed in these experimental formats.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Many companies are part of Alliance for Open Media, including Samsung, Vimeo, Microsoft, Netflix, Mozilla, AMD, Nvidia, Intel, ARM, Google, Facebook, Cisco, Amazon, Hulu, VideoLAN, Adobe, and Apple.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Apple is an AOMedia governing member, although it joined after the formation.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The management of the AV1 streams has been officially included among the typological videos manageable by Coremedia.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The first version 0.1.0 of the AV1 reference codec was published on April 7, 2016.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Although a soft feature freeze came into effect at the end of October 2017, development continued on several significant features.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The bitstream format, was projected to be frozen in January 2018 but was delayed due to unresolved critical bugs as well as further changes to transformations, syntax, the prediction of motion vectors, and the completion of legal analysis.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Alliance announced the release of the AV1 bitstream specification on March 28, 2018, along with a reference, software-based encoder and decoder.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 25 June 2018, a validated version 1.0.0 of the specification was released.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On January 8, 2019, a validated *version 1.0.0 with Errata 1* of the specification was released.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Martin Smole from AOM member Bitmovin said that the computational efficiency was the greatest remaining challenge after the bitstream format freeze had been completed.
[src:av1-codec/av1] While working on the format, the encoder was not targeted for production use and speed optimizations were not prioritized.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Consequently, the early version of AV1 was orders of magnitude slower than existing HEVC encoders.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Much of the development effort was consequently shifted towards improving the reference encoder.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In March 2019, it was reported that the speed of the reference encoder had improved greatly and was within the same order of magnitude as encoders for other common formats.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On January 21, 2021, the MIME type of AV1 was defined as `video/AV1`.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The usage of AV1 using this MIME type is restricted to Real-time Transport Protocol purposes only.
[src:av1-codec/av1] For AOM's 10th birthday, the Alliance announced the successor to AV1 called AV2.
[src:av1-codec/av1] It is designed to deliver better compression performance, enhanced support for AR, VR and split-screen usage and support for a wider visual quality range.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 aims to be a video format for the web that is both state-of-the-art and royalty free.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This concern has been raised regarding AV1, and previously VP8, VP9, Theora and IVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The problem is not unique to royalty-free formats, but it uniquely threatens their *status* as royalty-free.
[src:av1-codec/av1] To fulfill the goal of being royalty free, the development process requires that no feature can be adopted before it has been confirmed independently by two separate parties to not infringe on patents of competing companies.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In cases where an alternative to a patent-protected technique is not available, owners of relevant patents have been invited to join the Alliance (even if they were already members of another patent pool).
[src:av1-codec/av1] For example, Alliance members Apple, Cisco, Google, and Microsoft are also licensors in MPEG-LA's patent pool for H.264.
[src:av1-codec/av1] As an additional protection for the royalty-free status of AV1, the Alliance has a legal defense fund to aid smaller Alliance members or AV1 licensees in the event they are sued for alleged patent infringement.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Under patent rules adopted from the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), technology contributors license their AV1-connected patents to anyone, anywhere, anytime based on reciprocity (i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigation).
[src:av1-codec/av1] As a defensive condition, anyone engaging in patent litigation loses the right to the patents of *all* patent holders.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This treatment of intellectual property rights (IPR), and its absolute priority during development, is contrary to extant MPEG formats like AVC and HEVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] These were developed under an IPR uninvolvement policy by their standardization organisations, as stipulated in the ITU-T's definition of an open standard.
[src:av1-codec/av1] However, MPEG's chairman has argued this practice has to change, which it is: EVC is also set to have a royalty-free subset, and will have switchable features in its bitstream to defend against future IPR threats.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The creation of royalty-free web standards has been a long-stated pursuit for the industry.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In 2007, the proposal for HTML video specified Theora as mandatory to implement.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The reason was that public content should be encoded in freely implementable formats, if only as a "baseline format", and that changing such a baseline format later would be hard because of network effects.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Alliance for Open Media is a continuation of Google's efforts with the WebM project, which renewed the royalty-free competition after Theora had been surpassed by AVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] For companies such as Mozilla that distribute free software, AVC can be difficult to support as a per-copy royalty is unsustainable given the lack of revenue stream to support these payments in free software (see FRAND § Excluding costless distribution).
[src:av1-codec/av1] Similarly, HEVC has not successfully convinced all licensors to allow an exception for freely distributed software (see HEVC § Provision for costless software).
[src:av1-codec/av1] The performance goals include "a step up from VP9 and HEVC" in efficiency for a low increase in complexity.
[src:av1-codec/av1] NETVC's efficiency goal is 25% improvement over HEVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The primary complexity concern is for software decoding, since hardware support will take time to reach users.
[src:av1-codec/av1] However, for WebRTC, live encoding performance is also relevant, which is Cisco's agenda: Cisco is a manufacturer of videoconferencing equipment, and their Thor contributions aim at "reasonable compression at only moderate complexity".
[src:av1-codec/av1] It is therefore planned to support the color space from ITU-R Recommendation BT.2020 and up to 12 bits of precision per color component.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 is primarily intended for lossy encoding, although lossless compression is supported as well.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 is a traditional block-based frequency transform format featuring new techniques.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Based on Google's VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques that mainly give encoders more coding options to enable better adaptation to different types of input.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Alliance published a reference implementation written in C and assembly language (`aomenc`, `aomdec`) as free software under the terms of the BSD 2-Clause License.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Development happens in public and is open for contributions, regardless of AOM membership.
[src:av1-codec/av1] When the feature gained some support in the community, the experiment was enabled by default, and ultimately had its flag removed when all of the reviews were passed.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Experiment names were lowercased in the *configure* script and uppercased in conditional compilation flags.
[src:av1-codec/av1] To better and more reliably support HDR and color spaces, corresponding metadata can now be integrated into the video bitstream instead of being signaled in the container.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Frame content is separated into adjacent same-sized blocks referred to as superblocks.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Similar to the concept of a macroblock, superblocks are square-shaped and can either be of size 128×128 or 64×64 pixels.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Superblocks can be divided in smaller blocks according to different partitioning patterns.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The four-way split pattern is the only pattern whose partitions can be recursively subdivided.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This allows superblocks to be divided into partitions as small as 4×4 pixels.
[src:av1-codec/av1] "T-shaped" partitioning patterns are introduced, a feature developed for VP10, as well as horizontal or vertical splits into four stripes of 4:1 and 1:4 aspect ratio.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The available partitioning patterns vary according to the block size, both 128×128 and 8×8 blocks can't use 4:1 and 1:4 splits.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Moreover, 8×8 blocks can't use T-shaped splits.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Two separate predictions can now be used on spatially different parts of a block using a smooth, oblique transition line (*wedge-partitioned prediction*).
[src:av1-codec/av1] This enables more accurate separation of objects without the traditional staircase lines along the boundaries of square blocks.
[src:av1-codec/av1] More encoder parallelism is possible thanks to configurable prediction dependency between tile rows (`ext_tile`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 performs internal processing in higher precision (10 or 12 bits per sample), which leads to quality improvement by reducing rounding errors.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This allows the combination of either two inter predictions or an inter and an intra prediction to be used in the same block.
[src:av1-codec/av1] A frame can reference 6 instead of 3 of the 8 available frame buffers for temporal (inter) prediction while providing more flexibility on bi-prediction (`ext_refs`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] The *Warped Motion* (`warped_motion`) and *Global Motion* (`global_motion`) tools in AV1 aim to reduce redundant information in motion vectors by recognizing patterns arising from camera motion.
[src:av1-codec/av1] They implement ideas that were attempted in preceding formats like e.g.
[src:av1-codec/av1] MPEG-4 ASP, albeit with a novel approach that works in three dimensions.
[src:av1-codec/av1] There can be a set of warping parameters for a whole frame offered in the bitstream, or blocks can use a set of implicit local parameters that get computed based on surrounding blocks.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Intra prediction consists of predicting the pixels of given blocks only using information available in the current frame.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Most often, intra predictions are built from the neighboring pixels above and to the left of the predicted block.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The DC predictor builds a prediction by averaging the pixels above and to the left of block.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Directional predictors extrapolate these neighboring pixels according to a specified angle.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In AV1, 8 main directional modes can be chosen.
[src:av1-codec/av1] These modes start at an angle of 45 degrees and increase by a step size of 22.5 degrees up until 203 degrees.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Furthermore, for each directional mode, six offsets of 3 degrees can be signaled for bigger blocks, three above the main angle and three below it, resulting in a total of 56 angles (`ext_intra`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] The "TrueMotion" predictor was replaced with a Paeth predictor which looks at the difference from the known pixel in the above-left corner to the pixel directly above and directly left of the new one and then chooses the one that lies in direction of the smaller gradient as predictor.
[src:av1-codec/av1] A palette predictor is available for blocks with up to 8 dominant colors, such as some computer screen content.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Correlations between the luminosity and the color information can now be exploited with a predictor for chroma blocks that is based on samples from the luma plane (`cfl`), a technique borrowed from Daala.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In order to reduce visible boundaries along borders of inter-predicted blocks, a technique called overlapped block motion compensation (OBMC) can be used.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This involves extending a block's size so that it overlaps with neighboring blocks by 2 to 32 pixels, and blending the overlapping parts together.
[src:av1-codec/av1] It can combine two one-dimensional transforms in order to use different transforms for the horizontal and the vertical dimension (`ext_tx`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 has new optimized quantization matrices (`aom_qm`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] The eight sets of quantization parameters that can be selected and signaled for each frame now have individual parameters for the two chroma planes and can use spatial prediction.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On every new superblock, the quantization parameters can be adjusted by signaling an offset.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In-loop filtering combines Thor's constrained low-pass filter and Daala's directional deringing filter into the *Constrained Directional Enhancement Filter*, `cdef`.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This is an edge-directed conditional replacement filter that smooths blocks roughly along the direction of the dominant edge to eliminate ringing artifacts.
[src:av1-codec/av1] There is also the *loop restoration filter* (`loop_restoration`) based on the Wiener filter and self-guided restoration filters to remove blur artifacts due to block processing.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Daala's entropy coder (`daala_ec`), a non-binary arithmetic coder, was selected for replacing VP9's binary entropy coder.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The use of *non-binary* arithmetic coding helps evade patents but also adds bit-level parallelism to an otherwise serial process, reducing clock rate demands on hardware implementations.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This is to say that the effectiveness of modern binary arithmetic coding like CABAC is being approached using a greater alphabet than binary, hence greater speed, as in Huffman code (but not as simple and fast as Huffman code).
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 also gained the ability to adapt the symbol probabilities in the arithmetic coder per coded symbol instead of per frame (`ec_adapt`).
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 has provisions for temporal and spatial scalability.
[src:av1-codec/av1] A first comparison from the beginning of June 2016 found AV1 roughly on par with HEVC, as did one using code from late January 2017.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In April 2017, using the 8 enabled experimental features at the time (of 77 total), Bitmovin was able to demonstrate favorable objective metrics, as well as visual results, compared to HEVC on the *Sintel* and *Tears of Steel* short films.
[src:av1-codec/av1] A follow-up comparison by Jan Ozer of *Streaming Media Magazine* confirmed this, and concluded that "AV1 is at least as good as HEVC now".
[src:av1-codec/av1] Ozer noted that his and Bitmovin's results contradicted a comparison by Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications from late 2016 that had found AV1 65.7% less efficient than HEVC, underperforming even H.264/AVC which they concluded as being 10.5% more efficient.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Ozer justified this discrepancy by having used encoding parameters endorsed by each encoder vendor, as well as having more features in the newer AV1 encoder.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Decoding performance was at about half the speed of VP9 according to internal measurements from 2017.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Tests from Netflix in 2017, based on measurements with PSNR and VMAF at 720p, showed that AV1 was about 25% more efficient than VP9 (libvpx).
[src:av1-codec/av1] Tests from Facebook conducted in 2018, based on PSNR, showed that the AV1 reference encoder was able to achieve 34%, 46.2% and 50.3% higher data compression than libvpx-vp9, x264 High profile, and x264 Main profile respectively.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Tests from Moscow State University in 2017 found that VP9 required 31% and HEVC 22% more bitrate than AV1 in order to achieve similar levels of quality.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The AV1 encoder was operating at speed "2500–3500 times lower than competitors" due to the lack of optimization (which was not available at that time).
[src:av1-codec/av1] Tests from University of Waterloo in 2020 found that when using a mean opinion score (MOS) for 2160p (4K) video AV1 had the bitrate saving of 9.5% compared to HEVC and 16.4% compared to VP9.
[src:av1-codec/av1] They also concluded that at the time of the study at 2160p the AV1 video encodes on average took 590× longer compared to encoding with AVC; while HEVC took on average 4.2× longer and VP9 took on average 5.2× longer than AVC respectively.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The best-in-test AV1 encoder, Visionular's Aurora1, in its "slower" preset, was as fast as *x265 veryslow* while saving 50% bitrate over *x264 veryslow*.
[src:av1-codec/av1] CapFrameX tested the GPUs performance with AV1 decoding.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 5 October 2022, Cloudflare announced that it has a beta player.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 defines three profiles for decoders which are Main, High, and Professional.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:0:0 (greyscale) and 4:2:0 (quarter) chroma sampling.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The High profile further adds support for 4:4:4 chroma sampling (no subsampling).
[src:av1-codec/av1] The Professional profile extends capabilities to full support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2 (half) and 4:4:4 chroma sub-sampling with 8, 10 and 12 bit color depths.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 defines levels for decoders with maximum variables for levels ranging from 2.0 to 6.3.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The levels that can be implemented depend on the hardware capability.
[src:av1-codec/av1] A "Level 7" is mentioned but is not defined.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 video is usually accompanied with AAC or Opus audio in an ISO base media file format (MP4) container.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In October 2016, Netflix stated they expected to be an early adopter of AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 5 February 2020, Netflix began using AV1 to stream select titles on Android, providing 20% improved compression efficiency over their VP9 streams.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 9 November 2021, Netflix announced it had begun streaming AV1 content to a number of TVs with AV1 decoders as well as the PlayStation 4 Pro.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In December 2025 they reported that 30% of their streams use AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In 2018, YouTube began deploying AV1, starting with its AV1 Beta Launch Playlist.
[src:av1-codec/av1] According to the description, the videos are (to begin with) encoded at high bitrate to test decoding performance, and YouTube has "ambitious goals" for rolling out AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] YouTube for Android TV supports playback of videos encoded in AV1 on capable platforms as of version 2.10.13, released in early 2020.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In 2020, YouTube started serving videos at 8K resolution in AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In February 2019, Facebook followed its own positive test results, by saying it would gradually roll out the AV1 codec as soon as browser support emerges, starting with its most popular videos.
[src:av1-codec/av1] MSVP (Meta Scalable Video Processor) was announced and the symposis was published in a popular scientific research website on 15 October 2022.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 4 November 2022, the AV1 codec was announced with the article of Meta technology blog and with Mark Zuckerberg on Instagram Reels which shows AV1 codec compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Citing "Our Instagram engineering team developed a way to dramatically improve video quality.
[src:av1-codec/av1] We made basic video processing 94% faster." Android has preliminary native AV1 playback.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In June 2019, Vimeo's videos in the "Staff picks" channel were available in AV1 and Opus.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Vimeo is using and contributing to Mozilla's Rav1e encoder and expects, with further encoder improvements, to eventually provide AV1 support for all videos uploaded to Vimeo as well as the company's "Live" offering.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 30 April 2020, iQIYI announced support for AV1 for users on PC web browsers and Android devices, according to the announcement, as the first Chinese video streaming site to adopt the codec.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Twitch deployed AV1 for its most popular content in 2022 or 2023, with universal support projected to arrive in 2024 or 2025.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In April 2021, Roku removed the YouTube TV app from the Roku streaming platform after a contract expired.
[src:av1-codec/av1] It was later reported that Roku streaming devices do not use processors that support the AV1 codec.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In December 2021, YouTube and Roku agreed to a multiyear deal to keep both the YouTube TV app and the YouTube app on the Roku streaming platform.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Roku had argued that using processors in their streaming devices that support the royalty-free AV1 codec would increase costs to consumers.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In January 2022, Bilibili rolled out H.265 HEVC and AV1 encoding to videos with high view-count, while videos with lower view-count are only available in H.264 AVC.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In July 2024, DMM.com deployed AV1 on its DMM.TV service, becoming the first Japanese company to do so.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Other vendors had announced encoders, including EVE for AV1, NGCodec, Socionext, Aurora and MilliCast.
[src:av1-codec/av1] There are several hardware accelerators for AV1, typically as part of a GPU or system on a chip.
[src:av1-codec/av1] For example, later-generation NVidia GPUs have dedicated hardware and the NVENC and NVDEC APIs for encoding and decoding AV1 and other codecs.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In early 2019, Sisvel, a Luxembourg-based company, claimed to be forming a patent pool of patents essential to AV1.
[src:av1-codec/av1] This development has not caused Google to reevaluate its planned AV1 usage and the Alliance for Open Media has stated they remain confident that AV1 still overcomes the environment of "high patent royalty requirements and licensing uncertainty".
[src:av1-codec/av1] Sisvel began selling licenses to the pool, which contains patents from Philips, GE, NTT, Ericsson, Dolby, and Toshiba in 2020.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Unified Patents has been tracking challenges to various patents in the pool.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 7 July 2022, it was revealed that the European Union's antitrust regulators had opened an investigation into AOM and its licensing policy.
[src:av1-codec/av1] It said this action may be restricting the innovators' ability to compete with the AV1 technical specification, and may eliminate incentives for them to innovate.
[src:av1-codec/av1] On 23 May 2023, the European Commission decided to close the investigation while taking no further action.
[src:av1-codec/av1] But in an email they reiterated that the closure does not constitute a finding of compliance or non-compliance with EU antitrust laws.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In October 2023, patent pool operator Avanci announced the start of a new licensing program targeting video streaming operators that use AV1 in addition to H.265, H.266, VP9, etc.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In March 2026, Dolby sued Snapchat for Video patent infringement in the United States District Court for the District of Delaware (D.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Snap Inc.)) and in the Rio de Janeiro State Court in Brazil (Case no.
[src:av1-codec/av1] In May 2026, the 5th Business Court of Rio de Janeiro granted Dolby IP Bridge preliminary injunction against Skyworth.
[src:av1-codec/av1] The judge baned implementation of patented technologies in current and upcomming products sold in Brazil.
[src:av1-codec/av1] Also in the same month Malikie Innovations sued TCL Technology over AV1 patents in United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas.
[src:av1-codec/av1] AV1 Image File Format (AVIF) is an image file format specification for storing still images or image sequences compressed with AV1 in the HEIF file format.
[src:av1-codec/av1] It competes with HEIC which uses the same container format, built upon ISOBMFF, but HEVC for compression.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] An **inter frame** is a frame in a video compression stream which is expressed in terms of one or more neighboring frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The "inter" part of the term refers to the use of *Inter frame prediction*.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This tries to take advantage of temporal redundancy between neighboring frames, enabling higher compression rates.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] An inter coded frame is divided into blocks known as macroblocks.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] After that, instead of directly encoding the raw pixel values for each block, the encoder will try to find a block similar to the one it is encoding on a previously encoded frame, referred to as a reference frame.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This process is done by a block matching algorithm.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] If the encoder succeeds on its search, the block could be encoded by a vector, known as motion vector, which points to the position of the matching block at the reference frame.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The process of motion vector determination is called motion estimation.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] In most cases the encoder will succeed, but the block found is likely not an exact match to the block it is encoding.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This is why the encoder will compute the differences between them.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Those residual values are known as the prediction error and need to be transformed and sent to the decoder.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] To sum up, if the encoder succeeds in finding a matching block on a reference frame, it will obtain a motion vector pointing to the matched block and a prediction error.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Using both elements, the decoder will be able to recover the raw pixels of the block.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Because of these drawbacks, a reliable and time periodic reference frame must be used for this technique to be efficient and useful.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] That reference frame is known as Intra-frame, which is strictly intra coded, so it can always be decoded without additional information.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] In most designs, there are two types of inter frames: P-frames and B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] These two kinds of frames and the I-frames (Intra-coded pictures) usually join in a GOP (Group Of Pictures).
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The I-frame doesn't need additional information to be decoded and it can be used as a reliable reference.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This structure also allows to achieve an I-frame periodicity, which is needed for decoder synchronization.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The difference between P-frames and B-frames is the reference frame they are allowed to use.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] P-frame is the term used to define the forward Predicted pictures.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The prediction is made from an earlier picture, mainly an I-frame or P-frame, so that require less coding data (≈50% when compared to I-frame size).
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The amount of data needed for doing this prediction consist of motion vectors and transform coefficients describing prediction correction.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] It involves the use of motion compensation.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] B-frame is the term for bidirectionally predicted pictures.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This kind of prediction method occupies less coding data than P-frames generally (≈25% when compared to I-frame size) because the prediction is made from either an earlier frame or a later frame or both them.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Similar to P-frames, B-frames are expressed as motion vectors and transform coefficients.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] In order to avoid a growing propagation error, B-frames are not used as a reference to make further predictions in most encoding standards.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] However, in newer encoding methods (such as H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC), B-frames may be used as reference for better exploitation of temporal redundancy.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The typical Group of pictures (GOP) structure is IBBPBBP...
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The I-frame is used to predict the first P-frame and these two frames are also used to predict the first and the second B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The second P-frame is predicted also using the first I-frame.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Both P-frames join to predict the third and fourth B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] This structure suggests a problem because the fourth frame (a P-frame) is needed in order to predict the second and the third (B-frames).
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] So we need to transmit the P-frame before the B-frames and it will delay the transmission (it will be necessary to keep the P-frame).
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The last case allows the division of the block into new blocks of 4×8, 8×4, or 4×4.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The frame to be coded is divided into blocks of equal size as shown in the picture above.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Each block prediction will be blocks of the same size as the reference pictures, offset by a small displacement.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Pixels at half-pixel position are obtained by applying a filter of length 6.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Pixels at quarter-pixel position are obtained by bilinear interpolation.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] While MPEG-2 allowed a ½ pixel resolution, Inter frame allows up to ¼ pixel resolution.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] That means that it is possible to search a block in the frame to be coded in other reference frames, or we can interpolate nonexistent pixels to find blocks that are even better suited to the current block.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] If motion vector is an integer number of units of samples, that means it is possible to find in reference pictures the compensated block in motion.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] If motion vector is not an integer, the prediction will be obtained from interpolated pixels by an interpolator filter to horizontal and vertical directions.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Multiple references to motion estimation allows finding the best reference in 2 possible buffers (List 0 to past pictures, List 1 to future pictures) which contain up to 16 frames in total.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Block prediction is done by a weighted sum of blocks from the reference picture.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] It allows enhanced picture quality in scenes where there are changes of plane, zoom, or when new objects are revealed.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Skip and Direct Mode are very frequently used, especially with B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] They significantly reduce the number of bits to be coded.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] These modes are referred to when a block is coded without sending residual error or motion vectors.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The encoder will only record that it is a Skip Macroblock.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] The decoder will deduce the motion vector of Direct/Skip Mode coded block from other blocks already decoded.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] It uses the block motion vector from List 1 frame, located at the same position to deduce the motion vector.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] List 1 block uses a List 0 block as reference.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] It predicts the movement from neighbor macroblocks in same frame.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] A possible criterion could be to copy the motion vector from a neighboring block.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] These modes are used in uniform zones of the picture where there is not much movement.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] In the figure above, pink blocks are Direct/Skip Mode coded blocks.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] As we can see, they are used very frequently, mainly in B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] Video codecs such as MPEG-2, H.264 or Ogg Theora reduce the amount of data in a stream by following key frames with one or more inter frames.
[src:av1-codec/inter-frame] These frames can typically be encoded using a lower bit rate than is needed for key frames because much of the image is ordinarily similar, so only the changing parts need to be coded.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] In the analog video world, transcoding can be performed just while files are being searched, as well as for presentation.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For example, Cineon and DPX files have been widely used as a common format for digital cinema, but the data size of a two-hour movie is about 8 terabytes (TB).
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] That large size can increase the cost and difficulty of handling movie files.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] However, transcoding into a JPEG2000 lossless format has better data compression performance than other lossless coding technologies; in many cases, JPEG2000 can compress images to half their original size.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Transcoding is commonly a lossy process, introducing generation loss; however, transcoding can be lossless if the output is either losslessly compressed or uncompressed.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Transcoding is a two-step process in which the original data is decoded to an intermediate uncompressed format (e.g., PCM for audio; YUV for video), which is then encoded into the target format.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] image), one will generally decode it, edit it, then re-encode it.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] , and make all edits on that copy, rather than repeatedly re-encoding it.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Similarly, if encoding to a lossy format is required, it should be deferred until the data is finalised, e.g., after mastering.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] , but may use an identical sampling rate with higher compression.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] , and is used if the output resolution differs from the resolution of the media.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] One can also use formats with bitrate peeling, which allow one to easily lower the bitrate without re-encoding, but quality is often lower than a re-encode.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For example, in Vorbis, bitrate peeling as of 2008, the quality is inferior to re-encoding.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] The key drawback of transcoding in lossy formats is decreased quality.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Compression artifacts are cumulative, so transcoding causes a progressive loss of quality with each successive generation, known as digital generation loss.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For this reason, transcoding (in lossy formats) is generally discouraged unless unavoidable.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] These lossless formats can be transcoded to PCM formats or transcoded directly from one lossless format to another lossless format, without any loss in quality.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] They can be transcoded into a lossy format, but these copies will then not be able to be transcoded into another format of any kind (PCM, lossless, or lossy) without a subsequent loss of quality.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For image editing users are advised to capture or save images in a raw or uncompressed format, and then edit a copy of that master version, only converting to lossy formats if smaller file sized images are needed for final distribution.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] As with audio, transcoding from lossy format to another format of any type will result in a loss of quality.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For video editing, (for video converting), images are normally compressed directly during the recording process due to the huge file sizes that would be created if they were not, and because the huge storage demands being too cumbersome for the user otherwise.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Although transcoding can be found in many areas of content adaptation, it is commonly used in the area of mobile phone content adaptation.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] In this case, transcoding is a must, due to the diversity of mobile devices and their capabilities.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] This diversity requires an intermediate state of content adaptation in order to make sure that the source content will adequately function on the target device to which it is sent.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Transcoding video from most consumer digital cameras can reduce the file size significantly while keeping the quality about the same.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] This is possible because most consumer cameras are real-time, power-constrained devices having neither the processing power nor the robust power supplies of desktop CPUs.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] One of the most popular technologies in which transcoding is used is the Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS), which is the technology used to send or receive messages with media (image, sound, text and video) between mobile phones.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] For example, when a camera phone is used to take a digital picture, a high-quality image of at least 640 × 480 pixels is created.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] When sending the image to another phone, this high-resolution image might be transcoded to a lower-resolution image with fewer colors in order to better fit the target device's screen size and color limitations.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] This size and color reduction improves the user experience on the target device, and is sometimes the only way for content to be sent between different mobile devices.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Transcoding is extensively used by home theatre PC software to reduce the usage of disk space by video files.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] The most common operation in this application is the transcoding of MPEG-2 files to the MPEG-4 or H.264 format.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Real-time transcoding in a many-to-many way (any input format to any output format) is becoming a necessity to provide true search capability for any multimedia content on any mobile device, with over 500 million videos on the web and a plethora of mobile devices.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] Before the advent of semiconductors and integrated circuits, real-time resolution and frame rate transcoding between different analog video standards was achieved by a CRT/camera tube combination.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] The CRT part does not write onto a phosphor, but onto a thin, dielectric target; the camera part reads the deposited charge pattern at a different scan rate from the back side of this target.
[src:av1-codec/transcoding] The setup could also be used as a genlock.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] A **video codec** is software or hardware that compresses and decompresses digital video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] In the context of video compression, *codec* is a portmanteau of *encoder* and *decoder*, while a device that only compresses is typically called an *encoder*, and one that only decompresses is a *decoder*.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The compressed data format usually conforms to a standard video coding format.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The compression is typically lossy, meaning that the compressed video lacks some information present in the original video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] A consequence of this is that decompressed video has lower quality than the original, uncompressed video because there is insufficient information to accurately reconstruct the original video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] There are complex relationships between the video quality, the amount of data used to represent the video (determined by the bit rate), the complexity of the encoding and decoding algorithms, sensitivity to data losses and errors, ease of editing, random access, and end-to-end delay (latency).
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Historically, video was stored as an analog signal on magnetic tape.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Around the time when the compact disc entered the market as a digital-format replacement for analog audio, it became feasible to also store and convey video in digital form.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Because of the large amount of storage and bandwidth needed to record and convey raw video, a method was needed to reduce the amount of data used to represent the raw video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Since then, engineers and mathematicians have developed a number of solutions for achieving this goal that involve compressing the digital video data.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] In 1974, discrete cosine transform (DCT) compression was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] During the late 1980s, a number of companies began experimenting with DCT lossy compression for video coding, leading to the development of the H.261 standard.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] H.261 was the first practical video coding standard, and was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT, and Toshiba, among others.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Since H.261, DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards that followed.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] In 1999, it was followed by MPEG-4/H.263, which was a major leap forward for video compression technology.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It was developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The most widely used video coding format, as of 2016, is H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] H.264 is the main video encoding standard for Blu-ray Discs, and is widely used by streaming internet services such as YouTube, Netflix, Vimeo, and iTunes Store, web software such as Adobe Flash Player and Microsoft Silverlight, and various HDTV broadcasts over terrestrial and satellite television.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] AVC has been succeeded by HEVC (H.265), developed in 2013.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It is heavily patented, with the majority of patents belonging to Samsung Electronics, GE, NTT and JVC Kenwood.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The adoption of HEVC has been hampered by its complex licensing structure.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] HEVC is, in turn, succeeded by Versatile Video Coding (VVC).
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] There are also the open and free VP8, VP9 and AV1 video coding formats, used by YouTube, all of which were developed with involvement from Google.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Video codecs are used in DVD players, Internet video, video on demand, digital cable, digital terrestrial television, videotelephony and a variety of other applications.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] In particular, they are widely used in applications that record or transmit video, which may not be feasible with the high data volumes and bandwidths of uncompressed video.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] For example, they are used in operating theaters to record surgical operations, in IP cameras in security systems, and in remotely operated underwater vehicles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Any video stream or file can be encoded using a wide variety of live video format options.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Video codecs seek to represent a fundamentally analog data set in a digital format.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Because of the design of analog video signals, which represent luminance (luma) and color information (chrominance, chroma) separately, a common first step in image compression in codec design is to represent and store the image in a YCbCr color space.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It is common to represent the ratios of information stored in these different channels in the following way YCbCr.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Different codecs use different chroma subsampling ratios as appropriate to their compression needs.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Video compression schemes for Web and DVD make use of a 4:2:1 color sampling pattern, and the DV standard uses 4:1:1 sampling ratios.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Professional video codecs designed to function at much higher bitrates and to record a greater amount of color information for post-production manipulation, sample in 4:2:2 and 4:4:4 ratios.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Examples of these codecs include Panasonic's DVCPRO50 and DVCPROHD codecs (4:2:2), Sony's HDCAM-SR (4:4:4), Panasonic's HDD5 (4:2:2), Apple's Prores HQ 422 (4:2:2).
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It is also worth noting that video codecs can operate in RGB space as well.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] These codecs tend not to sample the red, green, and blue channels in different ratios, since there is less perceptual motivation for doing so—just the blue channel could be undersampled.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Some amount of spatial and temporal downsampling may also be used to reduce the raw data rate before the basic encoding process.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The most popular encoding transform is the 8x8 DCT.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Codecs that make use of a wavelet transform are also entering the market, especially in camera workflows that involve dealing with RAW image formatting in motion sequences.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] This process involves representing the video image as a set of macroblocks.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] For more information about this critical facet of video codec design, see B-frames.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The output of the transform is first quantized, then entropy encoding is applied to the quantized values.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The entropy coding method typically uses variable-length coding tables.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Some encoders compress the video in a multiple-step process called *n-pass* encoding (e.g.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] 2-pass), which performs a slower but potentially higher quality compression.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The decoding process consists of performing, to the extent possible, an inversion of each stage of the encoding process.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The one stage that cannot be exactly inverted is the quantization stage.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] There, a best-effort approximation of inversion is performed.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] This part of the process is often called *inverse quantization* or *dequantization*, although quantization is an inherently non-invertible process.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Video codec designs are usually standardized or eventually become standardized—i.e., specified precisely in a published document.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] However, only the decoding process need be standardized to enable interoperability.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The encoding process is typically not specified at all in a standard, and implementers are free to design their encoder however they want, as long as the video can be decoded in the specified manner.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] For this reason, the quality of the video produced by decoding the results of different encoders that use the same video codec standard can vary dramatically from one encoder implementation to another.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] A variety of video compression formats can be implemented on PCs and in consumer electronics equipment.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] It is therefore possible for multiple codecs to be available in the same product, reducing the need to choose a single dominant video compression format to achieve interoperability.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Standard video compression formats can be supported by multiple encoder and decoder implementations from multiple sources.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] For example, video encoded with a standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as Xvid can be decoded using any other standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as FFmpeg MPEG-4 or DivX Pro Codec, because they all use the same video format.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Codecs have their qualities and drawbacks.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] The trade-off between compression power, speed, and fidelity (including artifacts) is usually considered the most important figure of technical merit.
[src:av1-codec/video-codec] Online video material is encoded by a variety of codecs, and this has led to the availability of codec packs — a pre-assembled set of commonly used codecs combined with an installer available as a software package for PCs, such as K-Lite Codec Pack, Perian and Combined Community Codec Pack.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is the successor to VP8 and competes mainly with MPEG's High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC/H.265).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] At first, VP9 was mainly used on Google's video platform YouTube.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The emergence of the Alliance for Open Media, and its support for the ongoing development of the successor AV1, of which Google is a part, led to growing interest in the format.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In contrast to HEVC, VP9 support is common among modern web browsers (see HTML video § Browser support).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Android has supported VP9 since version 4.4 KitKat, while Safari 14 added support for VP9 in iOS / iPadOS / tvOS 14 and macOS Big Sur.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Parts of the format are covered by patents held by Google.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The company grants free usage of its own related patents based on reciprocity, i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigations.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is the last official iteration of the TrueMotion series of video formats that Google bought in 2010 for $134 million together with the company On2 Technologies that created it.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The development of VP9 started in the second half of 2011 under the development names of *Next Gen Open Video* (*NGOV*) and *VP-Next*.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The design goals for VP9 included reducing the bit rate by 50% compared to VP8 while maintaining the same video quality, and aiming for better compression efficiency than the MPEG High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC) standard.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In June 2013 the "profile 0" of VP9 was finalized, and two months later Google's Chrome browser was released with support for VP9 video playback.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In October of that year a native VP9 decoder was added to FFmpeg, and to Libav six weeks later.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Mozilla added VP9 support to Firefox in March 2014.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In 2014 Google added two high bit depth profiles: profile 2 and profile 3.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In 2013 an updated version of the WebM format was published, featuring support for VP9 together with Opus audio.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In March 2013, the MPEG Licensing Administration dropped an announced assertion of disputed patent claims against VP8 and its successors after the United States Department of Justice started to investigate whether it was acting to unfairly stifle competition.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Throughout, Google has worked with hardware vendors to get VP9 support into silicon.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In January 2014, Ittiam, in collaboration with ARM and Google, demonstrated its VP9 decoder for ARM Cortex devices.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Using GPGPU techniques, the decoder was capable of 1080p at 30fps on an Arndale Board.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In early 2015 Nvidia announced VP9 support in its Tegra X1 SoC, and VeriSilicon announced VP9 Profile 2 support in its Hantro G2v2 decoder IP.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In April 2015 Google released a significant update to its libvpx library, with version 1.4.0 adding support for 10-bit and 12-bit bit depth, 4:2:2 and 4:4:4 chroma subsampling, and VP9 multithreaded decoding/encoding.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In December 2015, Netflix published a draft proposal for including VP9 video in an MP4 container with MPEG Common Encryption.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In January 2016, Ittiam demonstrated an OpenCL based VP9 encoder.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The encoder is targeting ARM Mali mobile GPUs and was demonstrated on a Samsung Galaxy S6.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 support was added to Microsoft's web browser Edge in 2016.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In March 2017, Ittiam announced the completion of a project to enhance the encoding speed of libvpx.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The speed improvement was said to be 50-70%, and the code "publicly available as part of libvpx".
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is customized for video resolutions greater than 1080p (such as UHD) and also enables lossless compression.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] It supports resolutions up to 65536×65536, whereas HEVC supports resolutions up to 8192×4320 pixels.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The VP9 format supports the following color spaces (and corresponding YCbCr to RGB transformation matrices): Rec.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 supports many transfer functions and supports HDR video with hybrid log–gamma (HLG) or perceptual quantizer (PQ).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] An early comparison that took varying encoding speed into account showed x265 to narrowly beat libvpx at the very highest quality (slowest encoding) whereas libvpx was superior at any other encoding speed, by SSIM.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] By contrast, another subjective comparison from 2014 concluded that at higher quality settings HEVC and VP9 were tied at a 40 to 45% bitrate advantage over H.264.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Netflix, after a large test in August 2016, concluded that libvpx was 20% less efficient than x265, but by October the same year also found that tweaking encoding parameters could "reduce or even reverse the gap between VP9 and HEVC".
[src:av1-codec/vp9] At NAB 2017, Netflix shared that they had switched to the *EVE* encoder, which according to their studies offered better two-pass rate control and was 8% more efficient than libvpx.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] It was concluded that libvpx and x265 were both capable of the claimed 50% bitrate improvement over H.264, but only at 10–20 times the encoding time of x264.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Judged by the objective quality metric VQM in early 2015, the VP9 reference encoder delivered video quality on par with the best HEVC implementations.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A decoder comparison by the same developer showed 10% faster decoding for ffvp9 than ffh264 for same-quality video, or "identical" at same bitrate.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] It also showed that the implementation can make a difference, concluding that "ffvp9 beats libvpx consistently by 25–50%".
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Another decoder comparison indicated 10–40 percent higher CPU load than H.264 (but does not say whether this was with ffvp9 or libvpx), and that on mobile, the Ittiam demo player was about 40 percent faster than the Chrome browser at playing VP9.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is a traditional block-based transform coding format.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The bitstream format is relatively simple compared to formats that offer similar bitrate efficiency like HEVC.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 has many design improvements compared to VP8.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Its biggest improvement is support for the use of coding units of 64×64 pixels.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] This is especially useful with high-resolution video.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Also, the prediction of motion vectors was improved.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In addition to VP8's four modes (average/"DC", "true motion", horizontal, vertical), VP9 supports six oblique directions for linear extrapolation of pixels in intra-frame prediction.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In order to enable some parallel processing of frames, video frames can be split along coding unit boundaries into up to four rows of 256 to 4096 pixels wide evenly spaced tiles with each tile column coded independently.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] This is mandatory for video resolutions in excess of 4096 pixels.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A tile header contains the tile size in bytes so decoders can skip ahead and decode each tile row in a separate thread.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The image is then divided into coding units called superblocks of 64×64 pixels which are adaptively subpartitioned in a quadtree coding structure.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] They can be subdivided either horizontally or vertically or both; square (sub)units can be subdivided recursively down to 4×4 pixel blocks.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Subunits are coded in raster scan order: left to right, top to bottom.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Starting from each key frame, decoders keep 8 frames buffered to be used as reference frames or to be shown later.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Transmitted frames signal which buffer to overwrite and can optionally be decoded into one of the buffers without being shown.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The encoder can send a minimal frame that just triggers one of the buffers to be displayed ("skip frame").
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Each inter frame can reference up to three of the buffered frames for temporal prediction.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Up to two of those reference frames can be used in each coding block to calculate a sample data prediction, using spatially displaced (motion compensation) content from a reference frame or an average of content from two reference frames ("compound prediction mode").
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The (ideally small) remaining difference (delta encoding) from the computed prediction to the actual image content is transformed using a DCT or ADST (for edge blocks) and quantized.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Something like a b-frame can be coded while preserving the original frame order in the bitstream using a structure named superframes.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Hidden alternate reference frames can be packed together with an ordinary inter frame and a skip frame that triggers display of previous hidden altref content from its reference frame buffer right after the accompanying p-frame.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 enables lossless encoding by transmitting at the lowest quantization level (q index 0) an additional 4×4-block encoded Walsh–Hadamard transformed (WHT) residue signal.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In order to be seekable, raw VP9 bitstreams have to be encapsulated in a container format, for example Matroska (.mkv), its derived WebM format (.webm) or the Duck IVF format which is traditionally supported by libvpx, a library that originated at The Duck Corporation.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is identified as `V_VP9` in WebM and `VP09` in MP4, adhering to respective naming conventions.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Adobe Flash, which traditionally used VPx formats up to VP7, was never upgraded to VP8 or VP9, but instead to H.264.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Therefore, VP9 penetrated web applications only with the shift from Flash to HTML5 technology, which was still somewhat immature when VP9 was introduced.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A main user of VP9 is Google's popular video platform YouTube, which offers VP9 video at all resolutions along with Opus audio in the WebM file format, through DASH streaming.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Another early adopter was Wikipedia (specifically Wikimedia Commons, which hosts multimedia files across Wikipedia's subpages and languages).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Wikipedia endorses open and royalty-free multimedia formats.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] As of 2016, the three accepted video formats are VP9, VP8 and Theora.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Since December 2016, Netflix has used VP9 encoding for their catalog, alongside H.264 and HEVC.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] As of February 2020, AV1 has been started to be adopted for mobile devices, not unlike how VP9 has started on the platform.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Google TV uses (at least in part) VP9 profile 2 with Widevine DRM.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Stadia used VP9 for video game streaming up to 4k on supported hardware like the Chromecast Ultra, mobile phones as well as web browsers.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A series of cloud encoding services offer VP9 encoding, including Amazon, Bitmovin, Brightcove, castLabs, JW Player, Telestream, and Wowza.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Encoding.com has offered VP9 encoding since Q4 2016, which amounted to a yearly average of 11% popularity for VP9 among its customers that year.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] JW Player supports VP9 in its widely used software-as-a-service HTML video player.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] VP9 is supported in all major open source media player software, including VLC, MPlayer/MPlayer2/MPV, Kodi, MythTV, and FFplay.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Android has had VP9 software decoding since version 4.4 "KitKat".
[src:av1-codec/vp9] For a list of consumer electronics with hardware support, including TVs, smartphones, set top boxes and game consoles, see webmproject.org's list.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Hardware accelerated VP9 decoding support nowadays is ubiquitous as most GPUs and SoCs support it natively.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Hardware encoding is present in Intel's Kaby Lake processors and above.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The Sony PlayStation 5 supports capturing 1080p and 2160p footage using VP9 in a WebM container.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The reference implementation from Google is found in the free software programming library `libvpx`.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] It has a single-pass and a two-pass encoding mode, but the single-pass mode is considered broken and does not offer effective control over the target bitrate.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] FFmpeg's VP9 decoder takes advantage of a corpus of SIMD optimizations shared with other codecs to make it fast.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A comparison made by an FFmpeg developer indicated that this was faster than libvpx, and compared to FFmpeg's h.264 decoder, "identical" performance for same-bitrate video, or about 10% faster for same-quality video.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In March 2019, Luxembourg-based Sisvel announced the formation of patent pools for VP9 and AV1.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Members of the pools included JVCKenwood, NTT, Orange S.A., Philips, and Toshiba, all of whom were also licensing patents to the MPEG-LA for either the AVC, DASH, or the HEVC patent pools.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] A list of claimed patents was first published on 10 March 2020.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Sisvel's prices are .24 Euros for display devices and .08 Euros for non-display devices using VP9, but would not seek royalties for encoded content.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] However, their license makes no exemption for software.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] On September 12, 2014, Google announced that development on VP10 had begun and that after the release of VP10 they planned to have an 18-month gap between releases of video formats.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] In August 2015, Google began to publish code for VP10.
[src:av1-codec/vp9] However, Google decided to incorporate VP10 into AOMedia Video 1 (AV1).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] The AV1 codec was developed based on a combination of technologies from VP10, Daala (Xiph/Mozilla) and Thor (Cisco).
[src:av1-codec/vp9] Accordingly, Google has stated that they will not deploy VP10 internally nor officially release it, making VP9 the last of the VPx-based codecs to be released by Google.
